investigatingAgency.comments: Robert Doyle Eatmon was Essie Valentine's live in boyfriend. Robert (Always referred to as "Doyle" by family and friends)was Arrested April 29th, 2017 for domestic assault on Essie, On May 18, 2017 Robert was arrested for public intoxication with possession of handguns. July 11th Robert was arrested for theft of $1,000-$10,000 stolen property. On May 29th, 2017, the LE reports they came to Essie's home for violation of the no contact order against Robert. On June 10th, 2017, the LE purported that they again came out for another violation of the no contact order. Roberts daughter Danielle, left Tennessee on June 9th, 2017. She had been residing with Essie (Referred to as Elaine by family and friends) and her father Robert "Doyle" Eatmon. She moved to Florida. Robert moved to Florida after his release from jail for the theft charges. He was incarcerated on July 11th , 2017. Booked at 1:34 p.m. And released at 9:19 p.m. That same date, Robert "Doyle" Eatmon, moved to Florida. Before moving, Robert, gave his green, GMC, Jimmy vehicle to his Landlord to cover back rent. When Robert's daughter picked up her possessions from that home on June 9th, 2017, she was using Robert's white truck. Once the daughter arrived in Florida, at her mother's home, Robert's ex-wife, Susan Eatmon,travelled back to Tennessee in that same white truck, returned it to Robert on July 5th, 2017 and remained in Tennessee for the birth of their grandchild.. Robert was arrested on July 11th in Tennessee and his truck was then impounded. Tanya Landrum, Essie's daughter-in-law, was told he was purported to be using a scooter/moped in Lake City, Florida to drive to and from his place of employment and that he had rented his own residence there. Tanya was also told that the employer had paid for Robert's taxi ride to Florida, from Tennessee, to employ him as a. mechanic for "Nature Source". The employer is said to have known Robert for 20 years +/-. Robert purchased a truck after arriving in Florida and was given the title. The seller indicated that Robert never came to pick up the truck but another man came, with the title, and picked up the truck from the seller on October 22nd, 2017. Tanya Landrum shared that since her mother-in-law's disappearance, she has learned that Robert Doyle Eatmon actually had several "girlfriends". Also, Tanya has mentioned that the next door neighbor is a retired police officer and he did see the loading of the truck occurring when the daughter of Robert moved to Florida. Tanya has pleaded for months for the local Police Department to list her mother-in-law as a missing person. The police department told her they put a BOLO out on Essie. Tanya even reached out to psychics for help and shared that they see her deceased near sharp rocks. A local addict in the community that Essie resided in told Tanya that she had heard that a hole was found to have been dug on the property rented by Robert and Essie where they resided. That was not true, the police never reported such a thing. Tanya said there are woods, with a cave like structure in them, behind the mobile home that Essie and Robert lived in. The police purportedly indicated to Tanya that they did a bit of walking around there but did not enter the structure. Tanya asked if there were sharp rocks near that area and if they would again search there. No further search was reported. Also, Tanya indicated that Essie did live with the drug dealer she frequented at one time; this alleged dealer is the same person that told the police he believes it was late May when he saw her last. Essie has been estranged from her extended family due to her substance abuse and living in a different state from her family. Also noted is that Tanya Landrum was told that Robert was very upset with his landlord and Essie about her still residing in the rented residence that he was leased to pay rent on. Due to the order of protection, Essie had on him he could not reside there but he was still responsible for the rent. Robert gave his vehicle to the landlord before moving to Florida as a way to pay his back rent and with the agreement that any money made in the selling of the vehicle, by the landlord, that exceeds what was owed to the landlord, would be sent to Robert. It was told that $80 was sent to Robert after the sale of the vehicle by the landlord and the debt for past rent monies was paid. The landlord does not recall any personal items being found when he cleared out the rental for his new tenant. Tanya said he mentioned items in the shed like a washer, bed frame and such. An elderly woman is said to be the new tenant of the mobile home rental now.

"He shot him in the face," said Marie Parsley, recalling the night she claims she saw accused murderer Timmie Lee Bain, 49, shoot his roommate and co-worker with a shotgun outside the men’s apartment located on a hog farm near Mud Creek.

Parsley testified for the prosecution Tuesday afternoon during Bain’s preliminary hearing. Bain was bound to the grand jury on criminal homicide charges after the hearing.

Parsley told the court she had gone to Bain’s residence to deliver some food when she interrupted a loud argument between Mayo and Bain. She said they were drunk and yelling at each other and Bain was clutching a shotgun. Parsley, who has known the accused killer all of her life, said she tried to intervene and urged Mayo to get away.

"Man, you need to run," she told Mayo as he stood outside the secluded residence.

Mayo did not heed her advice and kept yelling back at Bain, she recalled. He went so far as to claim Bain didn’t know how to fire a gun. That’s when Parsley said Bain stepped outside and shot Mayo in the face from a distance of about 20 feet.

While witnessing the killing, Parsley said she wasn’t the only one there. She said four other people, including Bain’s son, showed up a short time later and helped clean up the murder scene.

"They cleaned up the blood and put the body in the pond," she recalled.

Parsley admitted she didn’t actually see the men throw the body into the pond but she did see the body floating in the pond a few days later and started to call authorities.

"You go to the police, I’ll kill you," she said one of the people who helped dispose of the body threatened her.

The men reportedly moved the body a short time later, hiding it elsewhere on the hog farm.

While the names of the three men and one woman who showed up at the farm shortly after the killing were given by Parsley, none of the others have been charged. Parsley has already reported the name of the conspirator who threatened to kill her. It is not known if prosecutors have negotiated their testimony or if they will be charged at a later date.

Sheriff’s investigator Bo Ramsey later testified that despite their best efforts, they have not found the murder weapon nor Mayo’s body. They will continue searching the hog farm for clues and remains.

On March 2, 1983 David Warner planned to go to a function at a small independent church a few doors up the street from his Beeler Avenue home. Later, he watched TV at a friend's house until 19.00, then told the friend he was going to his house, about 30 yards away.

The next morning his family discovered he was not at home, although his bed covers were bundled up in a way that could be viewed as a ploy to make it appear he was in bed.
At first, police thought David had gone off with some friends, or maybe run away.
Authorities launched a massive search, but no trace of David was ever found.
Foul play is suspected.
